ists\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;endler.dev&#x2F;2017&#x2F;rust-for-rubyists</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<li class=\"result-item-second-level\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h4>Rust in 2018 | Matthias Endler</h4>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>I wrote about the future of Rust before and it seems like nobody stops me from doing it again! Quite the contrary: this time the Rust core team even asked for it.\nI’m a bit late to the party, but here are my 2 cents about the priorities for Rust in 2018.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<a href=\"https:&#x2F;&#x2F;endler.dev&#x2F;2018&#x2F;rust-2018\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;endler.dev&#x2F;2018&#x2F;rust-2018</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li class=\"result-item-first-level\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"result-item-first-level__data\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3>Rust: Embrace Captured Identifier in Format Strings | (think)</h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>While playing with Rust recently I’ve noticed that most Rust tutorials suggest writing code like this:</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<a href=\"https:&#x2F;&#x2F;batsov.com&#x2F;articles&#x2F;2025&#x2F;11&#x2F;16&#x2F;rust-embrace-captured-identifier-in-format-strings\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;batsov.com&#x2F;articles&#x2F;2025&#x2F;11&#x2F;16&#x2F;rust-embrace-captured-identifier-in-format-strings</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li class=\"result-item-first-level\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"result-item-first-level__data\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3>100 days with Rust, or, a series of brick walls — brandur.org</h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>A few thoughts on Rust after a few months of regular use.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<a href=\"https:&#x2F;&#x2F;brandur.org&#x2F;fragments&#x2F;rust-brick-walls\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;brandur.org&#x2F;fragments&#x2F;rust-brick-walls</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li class=\"result-item-first-level\">\n\t\t\t\t\t